english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Sent to Envoy Seol Bubo Upon His Return to Court
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Ming Emperor, having received the Mandate of Heaven, proclaimed the completion of martial glory. With the Middle Kingdom at peace, he turned his benevolent gaze upon the four quarters of the world, deeming it right to nurture and settle them. Thus he sent forth envoys, dispatching them in all directions to proclaim his might and virtue, that each realm might bring order to its people. Envoy Seol, Bearer of the Imperial Seal, received the Emperor's proclamations and gifts of ceremony, crossed ten thousand li of treacherous seas, and came to this land as the bearer of the Son of Heaven's merciful intentions. The entire nation hastened to receive him with utmost reverence.

    When rebellious bandits threatened Liaodong, our Envoy sought refuge here. The gentlemen of our court, having spent time in his company, held him in respect and affection. Thus, when he departed before, our hearts were heavy with longing; now that he returns, our joy knows no bounds. Yet we grieve that his departure homeward comes so swiftly, leaving us no means to detain him. Therefore we scholars have composed verses together to present as gifts.

    I reflect upon this: Joseon was founded in the very year of Yao's reign in antiquity. Though we have maintained relations with the Middle Kingdom across the ages, China has never claimed us as subjects—indeed, when the Duke of Zhou enfeoffed the Great Master of the Yin, he did not make him a vassal. Later, when the three kingdoms of Silla, Baekje, and Goguryeo stood like tripod legs, each vying for supremacy, contact with China waxed and waned through the Qin and Han dynasties and beyond. Our founder, possessed of great talent and far-reaching vision, arose in the twilight of the Tang and unified the three kingdoms to reign over this land. From the Five Dynasties to this present age, nearly five hundred years have passed. Our customs differ, our languages are not understood—truly we are beneath the notice of the Middle Kingdom. Yet the refinement of poetry, classics, ritual, and music has not faded among us. We know to honor the Central States, and whenever a sage appears, we turn our hearts toward him as our guide.

    How much more, then, when the present Emperor shows no contempt for those of distant lands, but extends such gracious favor! Envoy Seol, moreover, possesses a steadfast and upright heart. He regards the treacherous waves that cannot be measured as though they were level roads, and in proclaiming the Emperor's virtue, he has brought superior and inferior into perfect accord, with not the slightest doubt between them. Thus shall our nation serve as a supporting pillar to our glorious Emperor through ten thousand ages—truly, this begins now. Let the Envoy remember this well.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'four quarters' (四夷) refers to the barbarian regions in all directions—a traditional Chinese geographical conception.
  - key: ''
    value: Liaodong (遼東) is a region in northeastern China that had been threatened by rebellious forces.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'Yao's reign' and the founding of Joseon connects to legendary chronology; historically Gojoseon was founded around 2333 BCE according to traditional Korean dating.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three kingdoms' are Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla, which were unified by the founder of Goryeo (王建) in the 10th century.
  - key: ''
    value: This preface celebrates the diplomatic mission while subtly asserting Joseon's autonomous status as a civilized realm that honors Chinese culture without being subordinate to it.
